{
  "id": "study-detroit-techno-001",
  "version": "1.0",
  "title": "Detroit Techno — Soul Engine",
  "subtitle": "The machine that remembers it was built by humans",
  "annotation": "Detroit techno shares the four-on-the-floor foundation with its Chicago cousin but carries something Chicago doesn't: a conversation between the kick and everything else. The snare and clap sit together on 2 and 4, doubling each other — one synthetic, one acoustic, two textures. Hats swing between a downbeat accent and a quiet off-beat ghost, creating the internal rhythm that makes Detroit feel like it breathes. The open hat landing on the 'a' of beat 3 each bar is the pattern's character moment — not a fill, a signature. The pickup kick anticipating beat 4 in bar 1 is what separates a pattern you feel from one you count.",
  "grooveProfile": {
    "swingFeel": "Tight 20-tick push on off-beats. More mechanical than Chicago, more human than Berlin.",
    "accentLogic": "Kick and hat share the accent conversation. Snare and clap reinforce 2 and 4 without soloing.",
    "microtimingTendencies": "Hat downbeats arrive with authority. Off-beats defer. The open hat sits slightly behind the grid."
  },
